ounty Wexford, Ireland":"Templeshanbo, County Wexford, Irsko"},"da":{"Abt 1145–1172":"omkring 1145–1172","1156–1203":"1156–1203","1172–1231":"1172–1231","1145–1172":"1145–1172","about 1172":"omkring 1172","1203":"1203","Abt 1145":"omkring 1145","1167":"1167","1145":"1145","1156":"1156","1231":"1231","1172":"1172","Long Buckley, Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Ireland":"Irland","Templeshanbo, County Wexford, Ireland":"Templeshanbo, County Wexford, Irland"},"nl":{"Abt 1145–1172":"circa 1145–1172","1156–1203":"1156–1203","1172–1231":"1172–1231","1145–1172":"1145–1172","about 1172":"circa 1172","1203":"1203","Abt 1145":"circa 1145","1167":"1167","1145":"1145","1156":"1156","1231":"1231","1172":"1172","Long Buckley, Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Ireland":"Ierland","Templeshanbo, County Wexford, Ireland":"Templeshanbo, County Wexford, Ierland"},"en":{"Abt 1145–1172":"about 1145–1172","1156–1203":"1156–1203","1172–1231":"1172–1231","1145–1172":"1145–1172","about 1172":"about 1172","1203":"1203","Abt 1145":"about 1145","1167":"1167","1145":"1145","1156":"1156","1231":"1231","1172":"1172","Long Buckley, Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Ireland":"Ireland","Templeshanbo, County Wexford, Ireland":"Templeshanbo, County Wexford, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Quincy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from any of several places in France deriving their names from the Gallo-Roman personal name <i>Quintus</i>, meaning ‘fifth(-born)’ + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>. The earliest bearer of the name in England, that of Saer de <i>Quincy</i>, ancestor of the earls of Winchester, was from Cuinchy in Pas-de-Calais, but the name may have been reinforced by immigrants from Quincy-sous-Sénard in Seine-et-Oise or Quincy-Voisins in Seine-et-Marne. A family of the name <i>de Quincy</i> held the title Earl of Winchester 1207–65. Descendants of this family later bore the name <i>Quincey</i> up to the time of the English essayist Thomas <i>De Quincey</i> (1785–1859), who changed his name from <i>Quincey</i> to <i>De Quincey</i> in 1796.","History: The American Quincy family were established in MA by Edmund Quincy in 1633. Fifth in descent was Josiah Quincy (1744–75), a leading patriot, who was sent to England to argue the colonists’ case in 1774. His son Josiah (1772–1864) was a powerful opponent of slavery, president of Harvard, and mayor of Boston, a post also held by several of his descendants. The traditional pronunciation is “Quinzy”."],"variants":[{"name":"Quincey","meanings":["English: variant of   Quincy  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1355923,"age":22,"year":"1167","julianDay":2147298,"description":"Arrival of Normans at Baginbun in Co. Wexford thus started 800 year struggle between English and Irish.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Quincy was born about 1145, in Ireland. He had at least 1 daughter with Basilia de Clare. He died in 1172, in Templeshanbo, County Wexford, Ireland, at the age of 28."},"et":{"Abt 1145–1172":"umbes 1145–1172","1156–1203":"1156–1203","1172–1231":"1172–1231","1145–1172":"1145–1172","about 1172":"umbes 1172","1203":"1203","Abt 1145":"umbes 1145","1167":"1167","1145":"1145","1156":"1156","1231":"1231","1172":"1172","Long Buckley, Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Ireland":"Iirimaa","Templeshanbo, County Wexford, Ireland":"Templeshanbo, County Wexford, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"Abt 1145–1172":"noin 1145–1172","1156–1203":"1156–1203","1172–1231":"1172–1231","1145–1172":"1145–1172","about 1172":"noin 1172","1203":"1203","Abt 1145":"noin 1145","1167":"1167","1145":"1145","1156":"1156","1231":"1231","1172":"1172","Long Buckley, Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Ireland":"Irlanti","Templeshanbo, County Wexford, Ireland":"Templeshanbo, County Wexford, Irlanti"},"fr":{"Abt 1145–1172":"environ 1145–1172","1156–1203":"1156–1203","1172–1231":"1172–1231","1145–1172":"1145–1172","about 1172":"environ 1172","1203":"1203","Abt 1145":"environ 1145","1167":"1167","1145":"1145","1156":"1156","1231":"1231","1172":"1172","Long Buckley, Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, Angleterre","I